posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: Marquee Moon is odd. It feels simultaneously familiar and unique at once, but close listening reveals an album that seems wholly unaware of the musical traditions of guitar music which had sedimented around the time of its release in 1977. It's the guitars on this album which stimulates most discussion. Guitarists Lloyd and Verlaine render familiar distinctions such as rhythm and lead obsolete, switching places as they see fit, there's almost a complete absence of distortion yet the songs still rock, but most surprisingly Verlaine's style (apparently) makes use of the familiar pentatonic scales but there's not a blues lick in sight. The album doesn't celebrate musical heritage nor seek to undermine it like their less musically refined punk contemporaries, it's just there, separate from it, which is bizarrely admirable.

>>114792740
Is there an example of a band that's fallen off harder? They went from really pushing the boundaries in multiple ways, from the sorta jam-rock/loose song structure and HEAVY shoegaze influence being at the forefront in Gish, being one of the first bands to really do either. Followed that up with two incredible albums, followed by an album so dark it made an album with "Infinite Sadness" in the title seem happy in comparison. Then after that they slowly start succumbing to more and more pop norms and becoming apart of the disposable music machine. ATUM is the absolute bottom, so binded in the chains of pop that it's impossible for them to make anything even remotely listenable. They went from making amazing, unique music unlike anything else in the mainstream to sounding indistinguishable from it. And it's not like they've kept the same sound and the rest of the world copied them to create that. They changed, they changed how their songs were structured, they went to more "safe" chords and lyrics, they went to more poppy mixing, they chose this. I hate to fucking say it because it sounds so damn cliche, but it honestly comes off as a desperate attempt for relevance, throwing away everything about you that makes yourself unique and different and adopting everything that is popular and safe. It's been a depressing decade watching them sink to deeper and deeper lows with every release.

>>114788022
A triad is the root-3rd-5th of a chord, it gives you the sound and feel of a chord. A C major triad sounds good over a C major chord. A C minor triad sounds good over a C minor chord. The only difference is the 3rd, which defines whether a chord is major or minor. When you know the major and minor triads, you can use them to play a chord progression and add some flavor with the 3rd & 5th rather than just chugging on the root note like a pleb. But you need to know where the root notes are on your bass so you know where to move your fingers to play a chord/triad.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T0dr3rH7zxI

This video might help idk I didn't watch the whole thing, but it's pretty simple once you understand it.

As for your bass, make sure the volume is up on your instrument as well as the amp. Check for wear on your cable and test with a different instrument if you can.

An unfortunate thing with tutorials is that, the more obscure/niche the thing you're wanting a tutorial on, the less likely it is that there will be one. I listened to a couple songs and I'd say.. Your best bet will probably be a combination of looking into beginner "ear training", and then perhaps finding some tutorials on songs by comparable, more popular artists that you like so you can pick up the technical skills to eventually learn Unwound songs by ear. Once you can say "yeah, I can play a few songs that sound about as difficult as this" you can pick some songs where the bass is easy to hear and just start matching what the bass player is doing. Slow the song down to 65-75% speed if you need to. If you're finding *good*, accurate covers you might also be able to sort of cheat a little and copy what the person in the cover is doing since they'll be a lot more prominent in the mix, and you can see their fingers.

>>114795337
Ignoring the obvious like there is enough money and education to go around for there to even really be interesting bands, the UK was at the forefront of culture for a very long time and it's still up there. It had fallen from grace within living memory for a lot of people and it's decline was accelerating. This created a profound anxiety and distress the country still feels to this day. The transition into a modern economy, the digital revolution, the intense urbanisation, and growing poverty were all huge issues you couldn't escape. In contrast Europe has always been behind because of the language barrier and the rest of the Anglosphere is more prosperous and big enough you can run away from problems as well as not having that same historical burden and baggage of being the most successful country and people of all time being reduced to a fringe member of Europe and alienated from it's colonial children. Even developed European nations like Sweden didn't have the same pensive struggle as Britain had lost its place in the world and the old ideas that held up the country were gone. Again, this is still apparent to this day here but we have broadly collapsed into a satrapy of America and just emulate their styles as Europeans once emulated ours. There's enough of a legacy that stuff still gets made here but we are long gone from being the beacon we once were.

Personally, I have to say that I never had much time for King Crimson. I disliked their first album and, apart from a track here and there, didn't find much I cared for on later albums either. To make things harder, they were contemporaries of Henry Cow and we were often pointlessly compared with them (especially Fred Frith who got foolishly compared/confused with Robert Fripp). But we never saw the connection really; they were working in a much narrower musical field than we were. And when they began to make big statements about their originality for improvising (around Jaimie Muir/Larks Tongues time) we found that frankly rather pathetic. But that was their way - after all Fripp claimed to have invented 'frippertronics', which is either a mark of ignorance on his part or outrageous arrogance, since every guitarist 'invented' that obvious procedure. I was not a fan of the other groups you list either, or Yes or Genesis for that matter, the quintessential 'progressive' groups. I don't think we had much in common with any of them. We certainly didn't learn anything from them. I, for instance, would have to go back to early Zappa, Beefheart, Barrett's Pink Floyd, Soft Machine, AMM, Sun Ra, Coltrane, Coleman, Stockhausen, Schoenberg and so on for influences. And for contemporary bands in the 70's, Magma, Faust, Samla Mammas Manna.

-Chris Cutler

The Who had arguably the greatest rhythm section of all time with Moon and Entwistle. There's really not much argument against Entwistle as the greatest bass player of all time.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ASJxApEz_YA
Certainly you could argue against Moon as the greatest drummer. But you could also make a pretty strong argument that he was. Without question he invented his own incredibly powerful and chaotic style.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NJH8DmPfVmU
So behind every one of Townsend's classic songs you had this absolute thunder of this unequaled rhythm section, and that's a huge part of rock music.
Daltrey was probably the weakest link in The Who, there are certainly many better singers out there. On the other hand it's impossible to imagine any of them singing with The Who.
For just a total rock powerhouse live, probably they were the strongest band ever.

posts.com:
I remember seeing The Dope Show on TV when I was 8 and being fascinated by it. My family just said I shouldn't watch it because it was bad, which only made me more curious. When I was 14 and I felt serious alienation and depression for the first time, The Nobodies was maybe the first album that really made me feel heard with those feelings, like somebody else felt that alienation. Which was important at that time, since it perfectly articulated what I was feeling, and made me feel like others understood. I didn't understand the banality of teen angst.

I still think Mechanical Animals is a great album, especially since now I'm very familiar with Bowie and glam rock. The rest of his discography I'm more critical of, though.

Antichrist Superstar is fine, but almost inherently inferior to Nine Inch Nails, given what it is - a shallow hard rock album with shallow NIN-style industrial sounds all over it.

I can appreciate Holy Wood for the nostalgia I have, and how much many of those singles meant to me when I was 14.

I think the unfortunate thing is that after becoming familiar with things like industrial and extreme metal, Marilyn Manson feels so tame by comparison. His whole point was to be extreme and weird, but when you discover the underground, suddenly he isn't really very extreme or weird at all. It sounds like a watered down version of that music, made for kids who aren't ready for Einstürzende Neubauten, Gorgoroth, etc.

posts.com:
I am OBSESSED with Wagner's operas. The medievalist visions they inspire in my mind are like nothing else. I see armored knights charging into battle, fair maidens in flowing dresses, and dragons breathing fire. It's like Game of Thrones, but with even better music (sorry, Ramin Djawadi).

Every time I listen to "Ride of the Valkyries," I imagine myself soaring through the skies on the back of a giant eagle (or maybe a dragon, if I'm feeling particularly epic). And don't even get me started on "The Flying Dutchman" - the ghost ship and the doomed love story give me chills every time.

But it's not just the grand, epic stories that have me hooked. The emotional depth of the characters is unparalleled. I have never related more to a fictional character than I do to Tristan in "Tristan and Isolde." That longing, that unquenchable desire for something just out of reach - it's like Wagner is speaking directly to my soul.

>>114729358
I hated Bach for a long time. I was obsessed with Beethoven.

But then I started playing the inventions and sinfonias. Then I started playing the Well Tempered Clavier. That kept me occupied for several years. In that time I also started listening to the B Minor Mass and the Brandenburg concertos.

Then I played the English and French Suites and now I bounce around between all of his works. I never got anywhere close to a professional musician, but I played enough Chopin, Beethoven, Mozart, Haydn and so on to have an appreciation for the music.

The thing about Bach is this: this guy didn't write music like anybody else. He didn't write music, he didn't write philosophy - he wrote scripture.

When I play his music the qualities that stand out to me above all else are his integrity and devotion. He is, in my mind, the perfect combination of academic and artist; of craftsman and theoretician.

His forms are not just "good" - they are perfect. He can be lighter than air, and more dense than gold. When he states the subject, he means it, and he uses it with integrity. He is the first artist that made me question, "What is music, really? Is this sound, or a proof?" His fugues are iron-wrought. His harmonic vocabulary second to none.

I can understand why his music inspires the devotion it does over the centuries. But then you contrast this absurd combination of poetic-scientist with Bach the man and it gets even more interesting.

Sex-obsessed (evidently, by his number of children), beer-obsessed, coffee-obsessed, quick to fight and confront, and living within a small area of Germany for his entire life, without apparent care for the world outside of Lutheranism, and without really appreciation from the world. Bach was not appreciated in his time.

He is hard to appreciate. I think Bach is the musician's musician. He's become something of a virtue signal among musicians. But that signal exists for a reason.

Mahomets Gesang D. 549 and D. 721
Klage um Ali Bey D. 140 (Part song and solo version) D. 496A

Der Flüchtling: Dishonest-sounding heroic tone.
Don Gayseros: I’m sorry, Don Who? Spanish exoticism.
Namenstaglied: Featuring a shoe-addicted daughter. The misogynist proto-“Sex and the City” of Schubert lieder.
Erntelied: The harvest is of the pretty young girls in the village.
Das Finden: Rather patriarchal.
Liebeständelei: Sad rhymes and a tad creepy.
Das war ich
An Herrn Josef Spaun, Assessor in Linz: Overly declamatory.
Hagars Klage in der Wüste Bersaba: Blindingly obvious that Schubert had never seen the desert.
Hagars Klage D. 5: Different music, same tediousness.
Der Hochzeitsbraten: Not problematic, but profoundly unfunny.
Beitrag zur fünfzigjährigen Jubelfeier des Herrn Salieri: “Gütigster, Bester, Weisester,” “So gut als Weisheit strömen mild,” and “Unser aller Großpapa.” This is sucking up in its purest form.

posts.com: I do not like this version for a few reasons. First, the ornamentation is way too much. The version I have is the Dover edition which was edited by Camille Saint-Saens. There are far less intrusive ornamentations in this version. In this version there are many “agremens” which look like they are “borrowed” from Jean-Henri D’Anglebert’s ornamentation table, which makes me question the authenticity of the ornamentations in this version. Also, the same-old virtuoso style of playing anything Baroque with tempo markings of “fast, faster, fastest” is the method here. Any student of French harpsichord music knows that the pieces are to be played with a variation of “notes egale” and “notes inegales”....and when an embellishment is called for the majority of French musicologists and composers have written that the music has to be slowed down somewhat when an ornamentation is played. In essence, the music has to breathe more than is played here. And when one makes the “transfer” from harpsichord to the modern grand piano one must make adjustments to fit the style of the French Baroque. It’s not a virtuoso’s time to show off here. Even “Les Soupirs” which is marked “tendrement” in my score sounds rushed and even clumsy and certainly does not sound “tenderly.” Of course this is my opinion so take it as you will.

>>114783965
choral works ain't the only game in town when it comes to classical music. If you want to really dive into the genre, you might want to branch out and check out other areas too.

Instrumental works like symphonies, concertos, and chamber music are a good place to start. These pieces focus on the musical composition itself, without any singing involved. This means you get to appreciate the composer's skills in creating complex harmonies and melodies, making for a truly unique listening experience.

Opera is another cool option - it's a mix of music, drama, and visual elements. It covers a wide range of emotions, from grand arias to intimate duets, all while telling a story through the music. It's like a musical, but way cooler.

And let's not forget about ballet music! It's the perfect companion to graceful and flowing dance movements. It often showcases the composer's mastery of orchestrating different instruments, making for a lush and immersive soundscape.

So yeah, while choral works are definitely worth checking out, there's so much more to classical music. Don't limit yourself to just one area - branch out and discover all the different facets of this amazing genre!

posts.com:
Opinions on viols/viola da gamba consorts?
It was a family bowed string instrument with frets and 6 strings, better for chords than violin family, but less loud, and with a smaller range (each instrument from double bass to treble had only like 2 octaves and a half)
It's what the aristocracy played until the French Revolution.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0tL1FjrC2ic

Youtube recommended me that by chance, by what looks like a group of middle class moms, and it became one of my favorite versions of Bach's Passacaglia. The harmonies are great.
I like seeing a guitar size tenor range bowed instrument, instead of something small like a viola. I wonder if it could be improved (louder, greater range) with modern building technology and steel strings.

Cancel culture didn't really exist in the music industry until #MeToo in late 2017.

Pre-2017, the only musicians who were ever truly "cancelled" were those who were literally locked up and thrown in jail for a crime they were actually convicted of.

Remember that Michael Jackson was pretty much universally mocked for being a pedo in the 2000s and yet nobody really cared about it. He still toured, his tours still sold out, everybody still listened to his music, there were no major protests against his involvement in anything.

The truth is that people caring about the moral character of musicians is a very, very recent phenomenon. It used to be the norm that everybody knew musicians were degenerates but they didn't care anyway. It was just seen as part of the job.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114791741
it sounds good anon!
if you wanna transition you could either do it smooth by crossfading your new loops in and matching their timing, hiding the fade behind other samples or melody if it sounds weird, or you could do a hard transition/breakdown where you abruptly cut/filter/downpitch/however you wanna end your first loop, pause, then start the next loop. I also think it sounds good in these type of songs when you make subtle alterations to the beat throughout so it doesn't get too samey and keeps the momentum going, like doing hats only for a couple bars, or switching to double time, and of course doing actual cut up breakbeats would be the epitome of this. anyways, I'd say you have a good start here!

It was the equivalent of those old movies in which some granpa was nostalgically listening to some gramophone music, as the vinyl disk kept scratching and skipping and some waltz from his youth was playing.

Vaporwave was this exploration of nostalgia for those closed aesthetic horizons from the past. Reliving the past as a virtual reality, like a video game. And getting some aesthetic thrill from looking in the technological past as if it was some kind of sublime mindscape, a world from the past that was stuck in its time and continued to exist in some virtual reality that you could access through music and visuals. A fascination with living in an artificial world from the past.

The oddest thing about it is that some people liked this kind of thrill even though they never lived those times.

Whatever works for you. Because the intervals on the strings haven't changed, just shift everything down two notes on the neck. If you know the standard tuning map, it's easier to just shift it down two frets - the chord shapes and scales will be the same.

Jazz is really good but I must admit something after listening to bebop, modal, and modern styles for years now.

Jazz sounds super fucking silly. It is very beautiful when its beautiful. But most of the time its honky and cartoon music, the tonalities are very silly at tyimes. not to say the line playing and tonal nature of the melodies are not superb but in terms of tonality its always based off of some easy going whimsical bluesy idea. even modal jazz which had a shot at being a lot darker in tonality, still came out beachy and playful.

classical has a much more serious and dark tonal nature. it depicts nature and pattern with its sound.
while jazz often makes me feel like I am eating some really good beans on toast and then there's a really beautiful line or chord out of nowhere.

both are flawless and the two western mediums of encompassing voice perception melodicism.
